      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Text Classification Is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Text classification"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " assigns one or more labels from a fixed set to a piece of text. It is the most common NLP task in production systems: spam filters, sentiment dashboards, content moderation, topic routing, and support-ticket triage all rely on it. The input is a string of arbitrary length; the output is one or more discrete labels."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Text classification pipeline: raw text → preprocess → vectorise → classifier → prediction label, with four classification variants shown below"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classification Variants"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Binary"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — exactly two classes: spam/not-spam, positive/negative. Use a single sigmoid output neuron."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multiclass"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — K mutually exclusive classes: news topic (sports/politics/tech/finance). Use softmax output; exactly one class is assigned."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multi-label"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — a document can belong to multiple classes simultaneously: a Stack Overflow question tagged [python, pandas, performance]. Use independent sigmoid per class."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Ordinal"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — classes have order: 1–5 star ratings. Can be treated as multiclass or regressed to a continuous score."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classical Approach: TF-IDF + Logistic Regression"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For many production use cases, a TF-IDF vectoriser with logistic regression reaches within a few percentage points of much heavier models and trains in seconds. Always start here as a baseline."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.datasets import fetch_20newsgroups\nfrom sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\nfrom sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\nfrom sklearn.metrics import classification_report\n\n# Load 4 newsgroup categories\ncategories = [\"sci.space\", \"rec.sport.hockey\", \"comp.graphics\", \"talk.politics.misc\"]\ntrain = fetch_20newsgroups(subset=\"train\", categories=categories, remove=(\"headers\", \"footers\", \"quotes\"))\ntest  = fetch_20newsgroups(subset=\"test\",  categories=categories, remove=(\"headers\", \"footers\", \"quotes\"))\n\npipe = Pipeline([\n    (\"tfidf\", TfidfVectorizer(ngram_range=(1, 2), max_features=50_000, sublinear_tf=True)),\n    (\"clf\",  LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, C=5)),\n])\npipe.fit(train.data, train.target)\n\nprint(classification_report(test.target, pipe.predict(test.data), target_names=categories))\n#               precision    recall  f1-score   support\n# sci.space          0.95      0.93      0.94       394\n# rec.sport.hockey   0.98      0.98      0.98       399\n# comp.graphics      0.92      0.94      0.93       389\n# talk.politics.misc 0.89      0.88      0.89       310\n#\n# accuracy                               0.94      1492"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Neural Approach: Fine-tuning DistilBERT"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the task involves subtlety — negation, irony, domain-specific jargon, or short texts where word order matters — a pre-trained transformer fine-tuned on labelled examples outperforms TF-IDF. DistilBERT is 40% smaller than BERT with 97% of its accuracy, making it a practical choice."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from datasets import load_dataset\nfrom transformers import (\n    AutoTokenizer,\n    AutoModelForSequenceClassification,\n    TrainingArguments,\n    Trainer,\n)\nimport numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\n\n# SST-2: binary sentiment (positive / negative movie reviews)\ndataset = load_dataset(\"sst2\")\nmodel_name = \"distilbert-base-uncased\"\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name)\n\ndef tokenize(batch):\n    return tokenizer(batch[\"sentence\"], truncation=True, padding=\"max_length\", max_length=128)\n\ntokenized = dataset.map(tokenize, batched=True)\nmodel = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_name, num_labels=2)\n\ndef compute_metrics(eval_pred):\n    logits, labels = eval_pred\n    preds = np.argmax(logits, axis=-1)\n    return {\"accuracy\": accuracy_score(labels, preds)}\n\ntraining_args = TrainingArguments(\n    output_dir=\"./distilbert-sst2\",\n    num_train_epochs=3,\n    per_device_train_batch_size=32,\n    per_device_eval_batch_size=64,\n    evaluation_strategy=\"epoch\",\n    save_strategy=\"epoch\",\n    load_best_model_at_end=True,\n    learning_rate=2e-5,\n    weight_decay=0.01,\n)\n\ntrainer = Trainer(\n    model=model,\n    args=training_args,\n    train_dataset=tokenized[\"train\"],\n    eval_dataset=tokenized[\"validation\"],\n    compute_metrics=compute_metrics,\n)\n\ntrainer.train()\n# Epoch 3 val accuracy: ~0.927 on SST-2"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zero-Shot Classification (No Training Data)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When you have no labelled data, Hugging Face's zero-shot pipeline uses an NLI (Natural Language Inference) model to score whether a text \"entails\" each candidate label as a hypothesis."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import pipeline\n\nclassifier = pipeline(\"zero-shot-classification\", model=\"facebook/bart-large-mnli\")\n\nresult = classifier(\n    \"The Fed raised interest rates by 25 basis points to combat inflation.\",\n    candidate_labels=[\"finance\", \"sports\", \"technology\", \"politics\"],\n)\nprint(result[\"labels\"])  # ['finance', 'politics', 'technology', 'sports']\nprint(result[\"scores\"])  # [0.76, 0.17, 0.05, 0.02]\n\n# Multi-label: set multi_label=True to allow overlapping classes\nresult_ml = classifier(\n    \"This Python tutorial covers pandas and data visualisation.\",\n    candidate_labels=[\"python\", \"data science\", \"tutorial\", \"finance\"],\n    multi_label=True,\n)\nprint(result_ml[\"labels\"])  # ['python', 'tutorial', 'data science', 'finance']\nprint(result_ml[\"scores\"])  # [0.98, 0.96, 0.91, 0.02]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
